WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:06.680 --> 00:00:09.790
&gt;&gt;Paul Zak: Here at Google London.

00:00:09.790 --> 00:00:15.539
This book is about 10 years of my life trying
to figure out why people are good and evil.

00:00:15.539 --> 00:00:19.890
That's the longest debate since humans have
been having debates, right?

00:00:19.890 --> 00:00:21.030
Are we good, are we evil?

00:00:21.030 --> 00:00:23.770
And, of course, the answer is we're both.

00:00:23.770 --> 00:00:24.810
But that doesn't really help us.

00:00:24.810 --> 00:00:25.960
The question is why, right?

00:00:25.960 --> 00:00:31.039
Why would I ever behave in a way that's compassionate
or kind or why would I behave in a way that's

00:00:31.039 --> 00:00:32.210
cruel or aggressive?

00:00:32.210 --> 00:00:36.149
So, let me start out by telling you a little
about two women.

00:00:36.149 --> 00:00:38.600
One of them maybe you've heard of, one of
them you didn't.

00:00:38.600 --> 00:00:41.780
The first picture is from a crime scene.

00:00:41.780 --> 00:00:46.460
This crime was perpetrated by a woman that
I interviewed in a San Diego county jail in

00:00:46.460 --> 00:00:47.460
California.

00:00:47.460 --> 00:00:50.550
So to picture her she's wearing an orange
jumpsuit, her hands are shackled in front

00:00:50.550 --> 00:00:56.820
of her to her legs and she was a 25 year old,
long time meth user.

00:00:56.820 --> 00:01:02.080
So that tells you when she started using meth
and she had served a prison term for possession

00:01:02.080 --> 00:01:05.570
of meth amphetamine and then was sent to a
halfway house.

00:01:05.570 --> 00:01:08.270
So, kind of transition her back into life.

00:01:08.270 --> 00:01:13.500
In this halfway house were 4 women living
together, so 3 women and her.

00:01:13.500 --> 00:01:15.619
And it had a shared kitchen and living space.

00:01:15.619 --> 00:01:18.930
And she and these other women kept on having
these clashes.

00:01:18.930 --> 00:01:24.180
So one day in the kitchen, the prisoner I'm
talking to, decides to stab her roommate 22

00:01:24.180 --> 00:01:26.200
times and let her bleed to death on the kitchen
floor.

00:01:26.200 --> 00:01:30.960
So we're going through this long interview,
you know, when'd you first start using drugs?

00:01:30.960 --> 00:01:31.960
Your family history?

00:01:31.960 --> 00:01:36.130
And I finally, she's already plead to murder
so she's agreed that she killed that lady

00:01:36.130 --> 00:01:38.040
and so I said, "Why'd you kill this woman?"

00:01:38.040 --> 00:01:40.240
"Ah, she bugged me."

00:01:40.240 --> 00:01:43.729
As if she's a fly that she's swatting on the
wall.

00:01:43.729 --> 00:01:48.630
Okay, case 2, this is a picture from the 1930s,
again a woman who is about 25 years old at

00:01:48.630 --> 00:01:54.320
the time and her name is Agnes Bojaxhiu and
she's Albanian.

00:01:54.320 --> 00:01:55.759
She's from a fairly wealthy family.

00:01:55.759 --> 00:02:02.350
At age 18 she decides she's gonna leave home
and join a convent called the Sisters of Loretto.

00:02:02.350 --> 00:02:05.940
It's gonna be very important, there's a quiz
at the end of this talk, so remember Sisters

00:02:05.940 --> 00:02:09.459
of Loretto cause it's gonna be a key part
of my story.

00:02:09.459 --> 00:02:13.180
So she goes to England for training, she goes
to Ireland, then she's posted to India where

00:02:13.180 --> 00:02:18.930
she spends her entire career ministering to
the poor, the sick, the untouchables as Mother

00:02:18.930 --> 00:02:19.930
Theresa.

00:02:19.930 --> 00:02:25.579
She never returned home again, never saw her
family, never saw her siblings, she dedicated

00:02:25.579 --> 00:02:27.579
her whole life to helping other people.

00:02:27.579 --> 00:02:31.249
So how do we get both those behaviors within
the human species?

00:02:31.249 --> 00:02:34.689
Killing people like they're nothing and reaching
out.

00:02:34.689 --> 00:02:39.049
So flip that around, think of your own lives,
right, you all look like pretty nice people,

00:02:39.049 --> 00:02:42.329
a couple of the guys in the back I'm not too
sure about but the rest of you look pretty

00:02:42.329 --> 00:02:43.329
good.

00:02:43.329 --> 00:02:49.709
So how can you, yourself, go from being nice,
relaxed, kind, smiling to being aggressive,

00:02:49.709 --> 00:02:51.760
grumpy, nasty?

00:02:51.760 --> 00:02:53.599
How does that switch occur?

00:02:53.599 --> 00:02:58.669
And so scientists have studied for a long
time the nasty part, the aggression, the fear,

00:02:58.669 --> 00:03:01.139
because that gets huge responses in the brain.

00:03:01.139 --> 00:03:02.459
But I wanted to ask the other question.

00:03:02.459 --> 00:03:07.610
What modulates us to be more like Mother Theresa,
more compassionate, more kind to reach out

00:03:07.610 --> 00:03:08.610
to others?

00:03:08.610 --> 00:03:12.579
&gt;&gt;Paul Zak: And this took me on a 10 year
journey.

00:03:12.579 --> 00:03:13.950
And I'll tell you a little about that.

00:03:13.950 --> 00:03:17.409
But before I do I want to give you an idea
of some of the fun experiments that we've

00:03:17.409 --> 00:03:20.110
run, not just in a laboratory, but in the
field.

00:03:20.110 --> 00:03:27.709
So this one happened right here in England
and I have a short video.

00:03:27.709 --> 00:03:28.709
[Cheering]

00:03:28.709 --> 00:03:31.300
&gt;&gt;female on video: Most people plan to make
their wedding special but this wedding in

00:03:31.300 --> 00:03:34.420
Southern England was a first for science.

00:03:34.420 --> 00:03:40.090
Nick and Linda had invited researcher, Paul
Zak, to take blood samples from them and their

00:03:40.090 --> 00:03:41.389
guests.

00:03:41.389 --> 00:03:46.439
It was a chance to find out what goes on in
people's bodies during this momentous bonding

00:03:46.439 --> 00:03:47.439
event.

00:03:47.439 --> 00:03:51.699
&gt;&gt;Paul Zak: The value of doing this as a field
study is that we have an actual real life

00:03:51.699 --> 00:03:52.699
event.

00:03:52.699 --> 00:03:58.000
So this way we actually go in, in a very natural
