00:04:15.200 --> 00:04:20.169
&gt;&gt;Paul Zak: We thought maybe during this wedding
ceremony people are bonding to each other

00:04:20.169 --> 00:04:21.630
and they're actually releasing oxytocin.

00:04:21.630 --> 00:04:27.020
So we measured oxytocin and we also measured
a cluster of other hormones that were also

00:04:27.020 --> 00:04:28.020
associated with reproduction.

00:04:28.020 --> 00:04:31.919
&gt;&gt;female on video: Zak found that the couple
and close family members

00:04:31.919 --> 00:04:34.080
&gt;&gt;female on video: had more extreme changes
in oxytocin.

00:04:34.080 --> 00:04:38.710
&gt;&gt;Paul Zak: Linda had the biggest spike in
oxytocin, a 28 percent increase in oxytocin

00:04:38.710 --> 00:04:40.569
before and after her vows.

00:04:40.569 --> 00:04:43.040
So she's really feeling the love.

00:04:43.040 --> 00:04:44.040
Who's next?

00:04:44.040 --> 00:04:48.949
The bride's mother, of course the bride's
mother is very engaged emotionally, and then

00:04:48.949 --> 00:04:50.960
the groom's father, and then the groom.

00:04:50.960 --> 00:04:54.849
And then further out are just some random
friends that we pulled.

00:04:54.849 --> 00:04:59.370
&gt;&gt;female on video: Testosterone is linked
to sex drive and studies have found that drops

00:04:59.370 --> 00:05:01.300
when men fall in love.

00:05:01.300 --> 00:05:04.420
Zak expected this to happen at the wedding,
