00:05:48.610 --> 00:05:50.199
who care about the outcome.

00:05:50.199 --> 00:05:56.039
&gt;&gt;Paul Zak: Okay, so that was one of the fun
experiments we've done outside the lab.

00:05:56.039 --> 00:05:59.860
But it's just a way to kind of demonstrate
that the kind of behaviors we're finding in

00:05:59.860 --> 00:06:04.379
the lab, that induce the release of oxytocin,
which I call the moral molecule, happen in

00:06:04.379 --> 00:06:06.490
our daily lives all the time.

00:06:06.490 --> 00:06:12.110
And I think that's why this work is very interesting,
is because our brains are living in this sea

00:06:12.110 --> 00:06:17.030
of chemicals and we're not always aware of
the chemicals that are being released and

00:06:17.030 --> 00:06:19.650
how they impact our behavior.

00:06:19.650 --> 00:06:23.050
So oxytocin, until we started doing these
experiments 10 years ago, was only known in

00:06:23.050 --> 00:06:26.620
human beings to facilitate birth and breastfeeding.

00:06:26.620 --> 00:06:32.020
In fact, one of my colleagues and I thought,
well, maybe oxytocin might modulate positive

00:06:32.020 --> 00:06:35.199
behaviors in humans, told me it was the world's
stupidest idea.

00:06:35.199 --> 00:06:38.620
Cause everyone knows it's just for birth and
it's not very important.

00:06:38.620 --> 00:06:42.350
So, "But men's brains release this too," I
said, "There must be a reason why."

00:06:42.350 --> 00:06:48.410
And in animals, oxytocin has been shown to
facilitate tolerance for animals that live

00:06:48.410 --> 00:06:49.410
together.

00:06:49.410 --> 00:06:54.110
So I thought, well, tolerance to, like, treating
people well, that kind of runs on a continuum,

00:06:54.110 --> 00:06:55.490
maybe this works on humans.

00:06:55.490 --> 00:06:58.240
Okay, great idea, difficult execution.

00:06:58.240 --> 00:07:01.590
So, oxytocin is a very shy little molecule.

00:07:01.590 --> 00:07:05.469
You have to coax it out of the brain, it has
a three minute half life and then it disappears.

00:07:05.469 --> 00:07:12.000
And, so, we're required some very tight experimental
procedures to get this thing to be released.

00:07:12.000 --> 00:07:16.249
And, again, before we start doing this, the
only ways known were birth, breastfeeding

00:07:16.249 --> 00:07:17.500
and also sex.

00:07:17.500 --> 00:07:20.569
All three of which are too messy to run in
my lab.

00:07:20.569 --> 00:07:25.070
So we thought well, maybe here's a way we
could induce the release of oxytocin in a

00:07:25.070 --> 00:07:30.909
way that I can do consistently over and over
and over, and would explain one of the mysteries

00:07:30.909 --> 00:07:33.990
of life which is why we actually trust strangers.

00:07:33.990 --> 00:07:39.830
So we used this task, a task that was developed
by a guy that won the Nobel Prize in economics

00:07:39.830 --> 00:07:43.361
for inventing experimental economics, now
called the Trust Game.

00:07:43.361 --> 00:07:44.840
And here's the task.

00:07:44.840 --> 00:07:48.890
So everyone gets recruited to be in this experiment,
you get 10 dollars if you agree to sit in

00:07:48.890 --> 00:07:53.199
these hard chairs for an hour and a half and
after lots of instruction and no deception

00:07:53.199 --> 00:07:56.729
at all, we never deceive people cause we're
the moral behavior guys, it would be bad karma

00:07:56.729 --> 00:07:58.499
to deceive people in experiments.

00:07:58.499 --> 00:07:59.499
Here's the task.

00:07:59.499 --> 00:08:03.449
You log into the computer, your identity is
masked with a secret number and you get paid

00:08:03.449 --> 00:08:07.229
in private when the experiment's over and
you get randomly matched with someone else

00:08:07.229 --> 00:08:10.499
in the lab, who also got 10 dollars for showing
up.

00:08:10.499 --> 00:08:11.660
And here's the task.

00:08:11.660 --> 00:08:15.009
There's a first decision maker and a second
decision maker in each pair and the first

00:08:15.009 --> 00:08:19.029
decision maker gets a prompt, by computer,
saying "Would you like to give up some of

00:08:19.029 --> 00:08:23.650
the 10 dollars you've earned for being here
and transfer it to the other person in the

00:08:23.650 --> 00:08:24.650
lab?"

00:08:24.650 --> 00:08:28.139
Whatever you give up comes out of your account
but gets tripled in the other person's account.

00:08:28.139 --> 00:08:33.580
So if you give up, say 8 of your 10 dollars,
you keep 2, but that person just got 24.

00:08:33.580 --> 00:08:39.010
So the second person gets a message saying,
"Guy 1 sent you 24 dollars, you have 34 dollars

00:08:39.010 --> 00:08:42.430
in your account, would you like to send some
amount back to that first person?"

00:08:42.430 --> 00:08:48.370
So you can see, if you think about this task,
the pie's gonna grow by three.

00:08:48.370 --> 00:08:53.209
But if you're the first decision maker, you
have to hope, believe, trust that this person

00:08:53.209 --> 00:08:56.209
is gonna, in fact, get the signal and return
the money.

00:08:56.209 --> 00:09:01.110
But, from the second decision maker's perspective,
whatever they return to you comes out of their

00:09:01.110 --> 00:09:04.440
account one to one, it doesn't get tripled
again, it's a pure monetary loss.

00:09:04.440 --> 00:09:08.350
Oh, I forgot to tell you, we're gonna stab
your arm with a needle twice and take four

00:09:08.350 --> 00:09:09.589
tubes of blood each time.

00:09:09.589 --> 00:09:12.329
So you're literally making decisions based
on blood money.

00:09:12.329 --> 00:09:15.370
So, why would you ever do this?

00:09:15.370 --> 00:09:20.101
So, what we showed is that the more money
you receive, as the second decision maker

00:09:20.101 --> 00:09:25.970
did earning trust, the more your brain releases
oxytocin and the more oxytocin onboard, the

00:09:25.970 --> 00:09:28.190
more you reciprocate.

00:09:28.190 --> 00:09:30.300
This is actually really interesting news.

00:09:30.300 --> 00:09:33.600
We have a biological basis for reciprocation.

00:09:33.600 --> 00:09:35.910
Essentially this is the golden rule.

00:09:35.910 --> 00:09:38.220
The golden rule exists in every culture on
the planet.

00:09:38.220 --> 00:09:40.019
It says if you play nice, I play nice.

00:09:40.019 --> 00:09:43.190
For 95 percent of people this is true.

00:09:43.190 --> 00:09:44.870
The 5 percent that don't get this are interesting.

00:09:44.870 --> 00:09:47.209
I'll tell you about those in a minute.

00:09:47.209 --> 00:09:54.290
So once we discovered that oxytocin facilitated
this reciprocal behavior, this, this trusting

00:09:54.290 --> 00:09:57.410
behavior, we had to really dig into this deeper.

00:09:57.410 --> 00:10:01.800
I mean, this is potentially very valuable.

00:10:01.800 --> 00:10:05.820
So not only do we measure oxytocin and blood,
we measure lots of other chemicals that interact

00:10:05.820 --> 00:10:08.940
with oxytocin and none of those had an effect
on this behavior.

00:10:08.940 --> 00:10:14.860
And, we developed an oxytocin nasal inhaler,
in which I can shoot synthetic oxytocin into

00:10:14.860 --> 00:10:20.759
the brain, safely, I've done this for about
700 people now, and we can turn on these moral

00:10:20.759 --> 00:10:22.820
behaviors like a garden hose.

00:10:22.820 --> 00:10:27.779
So not just trust, but things like generosity,
where to be generous towards you means I have

00:10:27.779 --> 00:10:30.459
to lose money myself.

00:10:30.459 --> 00:10:37.990
Things like being compassionate, being charitable,
giving money to charity, so once we stimulate

00:10:37.990 --> 00:10:42.460
the brain, release oxytocin or shoot this
into your brain synthetically, all of a sudden

00:10:42.460 --> 00:10:44.100
people are reaching out to others.

00:10:44.100 --> 00:10:49.490
So, one way to think about this is, oxytocin
evolved in mammals to motivate care for offspring.

00:10:49.490 --> 00:10:54.279
And in humans, this system works so powerfully,
because we have these little parasites called

00:10:54.279 --> 00:10:59.510
children attached to us for so long that we
attach to all kinds of people, including strangers.

00:10:59.510 --> 00:11:04.560
But I think that's one of the great triumphs
of the human species, is that we can extract

00:11:04.560 --> 00:11:06.860
value from social relationships.

00:11:06.860 --> 00:11:11.430
And sometimes that value is from romantic
partners or friendships, but we can actually

00:11:11.430 --> 00:11:16.519
interact with strangers and get lots of value
out of those relationships, sometimes economic

00:11:16.519 --> 00:11:17.519
value.

00:11:17.519 --> 00:11:19.230
So how do we all work together?

00:11:19.230 --> 00:11:24.370
Again, so if you guys were rats in this room,
fur would be flying.

00:11:24.370 --> 00:11:26.310
Rats who don't know each other don't like
each other.

00:11:26.310 --> 00:11:31.660
But, again, most people here look pretty comfortable
and relaxed, how do we do that?

00:11:31.660 --> 00:11:36.880
Because we have something in our heads, oxytocin,
that says, "Johnny, perfectly safe.

00:11:36.880 --> 00:11:38.430
Seems to be a great guy and

00:11:38.430 --> 00:11:39.600
&gt;&gt;audience member: Michael.

00:11:39.600 --> 00:11:43.490
&gt;&gt;Paul Zak: Michael, kind of sketchy, don't
wanna be around Michael."

00:11:43.490 --> 00:11:47.670
So, again, if we didn't have that in our heads
we couldn't modulate the appropriate behavior.

00:11:47.670 --> 00:11:49.861
So, for Michael, I wanna go in and fight with
him.

00:11:49.861 --> 00:11:54.970
I have different chemicals that tell me, like
testosterone, that tells me how to do that.

00:11:54.970 --> 00:11:57.199
Okay, so that's the basic outline.

00:11:57.199 --> 00:12:01.100
The open question, though, is what it feels
like when your brain releases oxytocin.

00:12:01.100 --> 00:12:06.240
So we ran an experiment, designed by one of
my former graduate students now a faculty

00:12:06.240 --> 00:12:09.790
member with me, George Barazza which we had
people watch a very sad video.

00:12:09.790 --> 00:12:14.790
A hundred second video of a father and his
two year old son, the son's name is Ben and

00:12:14.790 --> 00:12:15.990
he has terminal brain cancer.

00:12:15.990 --> 00:12:19.490
These are not actors, these are real people
and Ben has actually now died.

00:12:19.490 --> 00:12:24.190
So, I'm not gonna show you the video because
the last time I showed it was at a law conference

00:12:24.190 --> 00:12:26.569
and several lawyers actually cried.

00:12:26.569 --> 00:12:29.649
And you know lawyers don't have souls so,
you know, I don't wanna make you nice people

00:12:29.649 --> 00:12:30.649
cry.

00:12:30.649 --> 00:12:32.209
Anyway, it's a very emotional video.

00:12:32.209 --> 00:12:35.480
There's a control video in which Ben and his
father are just at the zoo, there's no mention

00:12:35.480 --> 00:12:37.510
of cancer or death.

00:12:37.510 --> 00:12:41.190
So for the treatment video, the father actually
talks to the camera and talks about how it

00:12:41.190 --> 00:12:44.420
knows to feel to know his son is gonna die
in a couple months.

00:12:44.420 --> 00:12:49.779
And the son doesn't know it; he's just a happy
little kid, going through chemo, whatever.

00:12:49.779 --> 00:12:55.380
We get a 47 percent increase in oxytocin,
huge, just enormous increase, and people are

00:12:55.380 --> 00:12:59.210
more generous to strangers in the lab with
the money they earn for being there.

00:12:59.210 --> 00:13:03.170
They donate more money to the charity that
produced this ad.

00:13:03.170 --> 00:13:07.790
But they reported feeling the experience of
empathy.

00:13:07.790 --> 00:13:12.350
So the change in oxytocin correlated positively
with the sense of empathy.

00:13:12.350 --> 00:13:15.500
So it seems to be empathy that oxytocin makes
us feel.

00:13:15.500 --> 00:13:19.290
So, again, when I release oxytocin, I'm more
connected to you emotionally.

00:13:19.290 --> 00:13:24.190
I'm better able to forecast your emotions
and, therefore, understand what you're likely

00:13:24.190 --> 00:13:25.190
to do.

00:13:25.190 --> 00:13:28.029
This is pretty useful when you're around strangers.

00:13:28.029 --> 00:13:31.380
So, why is that useful?

00:13:31.380 --> 00:13:37.579
Well, that's consistent with human beings
having to modulate our behavior to fit the

00:13:37.579 --> 00:13:38.579
environment we're in.

00:13:38.579 --> 00:13:44.530
Alright, so if I have a sense of empathy then
I can figure out if you're gonna be aggressive,

00:13:44.530 --> 00:13:49.040
if you're gonna be dangerous, if you're gonna
