then you have the value of those social relationships.

00:28:19.960 --> 00:28:25.060
So I don't think churches are disappearing,
but maybe in Europe, we'll see.

00:28:25.060 --> 00:28:30.410
Okay, so one more question really bugged me,
which is all the studies I've shown you so

00:28:30.410 --> 00:28:33.350
far have been run either in Western Europe
or the U.S.

00:28:33.350 --> 00:28:37.660
And I thought, if we're really building a
theory, a biological theory, about morality,

00:28:37.660 --> 00:28:42.210
oxytocin release has gotta be universal for
this theory to be universal.

00:28:42.210 --> 00:28:46.540
So last year, I went to the Highlands of Papua
New Guinea to run an experiment.

00:28:46.540 --> 00:28:52.310
So this is our rain forest in which there
are 800 distinct languages cause these tribes

00:28:52.310 --> 00:28:56.410
of subsistence farmers are very isolated and
they can be very aggressive.

00:28:56.410 --> 00:28:59.120
50 years ago, they were cannibals.

00:28:59.120 --> 00:29:01.990
So I get there, and this is like the experiment
from hell.

00:29:01.990 --> 00:29:05.440
Everything that could go wrong, did go wrong,
other than someone getting seriously hurt

00:29:05.440 --> 00:29:06.970
or killed.

00:29:06.970 --> 00:29:08.830
No electricity, no running water.

00:29:08.830 --> 00:29:13.770
So we brought generators, I brought all my
own medical equipment, but, anyway, there

00:29:13.770 --> 00:29:18.210
were lots of issues that made it a very difficult
experiment to run.

00:29:18.210 --> 00:29:23.560
But we had these individuals do a typical
ritual that they would engage in, in their

00:29:23.560 --> 00:29:26.330
village, and let me show you what it looks
like then tell you about it.

00:29:26.330 --> 00:29:27.330
[Music plays]

00:29:27.330 --> 00:29:28.330
&gt;&gt;Paul Zak: It's in Japanese.

00:29:28.330 --> 00:29:29.330
I can, if you wanna hear it.

00:29:29.330 --> 00:29:30.330
Any Japanese speakers?

00:29:30.330 --> 00:29:34.600
[Music plays with Japanese narration]

00:29:34.600 --> 00:29:40.720
&gt;&gt;Paul Zak: So this was a Japanese documentary
on human evolution and so the camera crew

00:29:40.720 --> 00:29:44.990
followed me for this experiment
[marching noise]

00:29:44.990 --> 00:29:52.020
&gt;&gt;Paul Zak: So these are people living in
a village called Malke, there's about a thousand

00:29:52.020 --> 00:29:53.020
people there.

00:29:53.020 --> 00:29:58.140
This is a traditional war dance that they
do.

00:29:58.140 --> 00:30:00.070
[Murmuring]
[Japanese speaking]

00:30:00.070 --> 00:30:02.610
&gt;&gt;Paul Zak: And we took blood before and after.

00:30:02.610 --> 00:30:05.030
Before and after to find out what goes on
in the brain during this period.

00:30:05.030 --> 00:30:10.280
[Music plays]
&gt;&gt;Paul Zak: Like I said, there's no electricity.

00:30:10.280 --> 00:30:15.980
This is a hand crank centrifuge, we actually
brought a generator but my electrical centrifuge

00:30:15.980 --> 00:30:20.610
started burning up and so we had to crank
some of the blood by hand which is, 10 minutes

00:30:20.610 --> 00:30:23.620
by hand is a lot of work.

00:30:23.620 --> 00:30:26.060
[Music plays]
[Japanese speaking]

00:30:26.060 --> 00:30:30.190
&gt;&gt;Paul Zak: None of these men had ever been
to a doctor or dentist.

00:30:30.190 --> 00:30:32.090
They'd never seen their blood drawn before.

00:30:32.090 --> 00:30:37.710
And because there's no running water, although
it rains, we had to use like 5 or 6 alcohol

00:30:37.710 --> 00:30:40.350
swabs just to get to skin.

00:30:40.350 --> 00:30:41.400
I mean, they're kind of covered with dirt.

00:30:41.400 --> 00:30:47.100
They live in a wet, muddy area.

00:30:47.100 --> 00:30:52.260
[Japanese speaking]
[Music plays]

00:30:52.260 --> 00:31:03.450
[Japanese speaking]
&gt;&gt;Paul Zak: So, the other things we measured

00:31:03.450 --> 00:31:13.010
were testosterone, stress hormones and oxytocin
release because they all interact with each

00:31:13.010 --> 00:31:14.850
other.

00:31:14.850 --> 00:31:18.520
[Japanese speaking]

00:31:18.520 --> 00:31:36.170
&gt;&gt;Paul Zak: So you can 
hear my perfect Japanese on that tape.

00:31:36.170 --> 00:31:40.640
So what we found is, indeed, 60 percent of
the men in this ritual released oxytocin and

00:31:40.640 --> 00:31:44.580
they felt closer to their community in this
ritual that they had done for thousands of

00:31:44.580 --> 00:31:45.620
years.

00:31:45.620 --> 00:31:53.110
So the release of oxytocin appears to be universal,
almost everyone has it and I think harvesting

00:31:53.110 --> 00:31:56.680
this power can be quite valuable.

00:31:56.680 --> 00:32:03.100
So, because stress, like survival stress,
inhibits the release of oxytocin, it also

00:32:03.100 --> 00:32:08.440
inhibits our ability to feel empathy and to
connect to others and so there's this possibility

00:32:08.440 --> 00:32:13.210
that there's this positive feedback loop in
which as I release oxytocin, I engage in more

00:32:13.210 --> 00:32:18.830
moral behaviors, including trusting behaviors,
which allows for more extraction of social

00:32:18.830 --> 00:32:21.610
value from in relationships including the
economic value.

00:32:21.610 --> 00:32:27.330
And as I move people out of poverty, I give
them the luxury of releasing oxytocin and

00:32:27.330 --> 00:32:32.340
behaving in those social ways, and so this
feedback loop can start occurring.

00:32:32.340 --> 00:32:36.370
Of course you can unwind this, you can do
this backwards, we see lots of countries doing

00:32:36.370 --> 00:32:37.370
this.

00:32:37.370 --> 00:32:44.160
So if this feedback loop is real, we should
be able to see a data at the country level

00:32:44.160 --> 00:32:45.580
suggesting this is happening.

00:32:45.580 --> 00:32:47.390
And, in fact, we do see that.

00:32:47.390 --> 00:32:48.580
This is data on tolerance.

00:32:48.580 --> 00:32:53.270
It's a little hard to read but it's a strong
income gradient on measures of tolerance,

00:32:53.270 --> 00:32:55.580
the ability to tolerate people that are different
than you.

00:32:55.580 --> 00:32:59.530
There's a nice income gradient for things
like trust and there's even income gradient

00:32:59.530 --> 00:33:01.260
for happiness.

00:33:01.260 --> 00:33:07.850
So countries that are more tolerant, more
trusting are more prosperous and are happier.

00:33:07.850 --> 00:33:11.760
And, in fact, we found the same thing at the
level of individuals.

00:33:11.760 --> 00:33:17.460
In a recent experiment, which we look at the
differences in oxytocin release, we asked,

00:33:17.460 --> 00:33:21.190
"What's the difference between people who
release lots of oxytocin when they're trusting

00:33:21.190 --> 00:33:23.240
versus those who release little?"

00:33:23.240 --> 00:33:27.350
And the people who released the most were,
in fact, happier in their lives and they were

00:33:27.350 --> 00:33:32.110
happier because they had better relationships
of all types, better romantic relationships,

00:33:32.110 --> 00:33:37.380
more close friends, closer to family, they're
even nicer to strangers in laboratory tests.

00:33:37.380 --> 00:33:42.740
So, we looked at many ways to release oxytocin
and one of those is touch.

00:33:42.740 --> 00:33:48.230
Now, one our early experiments, we showed
that touch induces oxytocin release and so

00:33:48.230 --> 00:33:50.260
you have to believe your own research.

00:33:50.260 --> 00:33:54.061
So I started changing my life because of my
own research and one of the things I refuse

00:33:54.061 --> 00:33:56.990
to do is I refuse to handshake now, I hug
everybody.

00:33:56.990 --> 00:34:01.380
And, so, the students in my lab started calling
me Doctor Love as kind of a joke.

00:34:01.380 --> 00:34:06.661
Anyways, I had this reporter a couple years
ago from Fast Company magazine come to the

00:34:06.661 --> 00:34:10.629
lab, run through some experiments and then
he added me as Doctor Love in the title of

00:34:10.629 --> 00:34:12.329
his article about me.

00:34:12.329 --> 00:34:15.099
And at first I was kind of unhappy cause I'm
a serious scientist.

00:34:15.099 --> 00:34:19.839
Then I started thinking, like, what thing
could I do better in the world than encourage

00:34:19.839 --> 00:34:22.629
people to connect more, to show more love.

00:34:22.629 --> 00:34:24.700
In fact, oxytocin is just like love.

00:34:24.700 --> 00:34:28.460
You can't force someone to love you and you
can't force your own brain to release oxytocin.

00:34:28.460 --> 00:34:33.029
You can only give it to somebody else and
if you give it to somebody else, 95 percent

00:34:33.029 --> 00:34:38.139
of those people, they're likely to reciprocate
and show you that love, that care, that empathy

00:34:38.139 --> 00:34:39.619
in return.

00:34:39.619 --> 00:34:42.190
So I think, if I'm Doctor Love, fine.

00:34:42.190 --> 00:34:45.799
If I can encourage people to be more connecting,
more loving, I think I've done something good

00:34:45.799 --> 00:34:46.799
in the world.

00:34:46.799 --> 00:34:50.810
So, anyway, the book has a lot of practical
ways that you can do that besides just hugging

00:34:50.810 --> 00:34:51.810
people.

00:34:51.810 --> 00:34:58.960
And I think what it means is that we can take
charge of our social lives and build communities

00:34:58.960 --> 00:35:05.289
that allow us to foster better social relationships
and more happiness.

00:35:05.289 --> 00:35:09.650
So, understanding how to harness the power
of oxytocin, I think, is potentially very

00:35:09.650 --> 00:35:10.650
valuable.

00:35:10.650 --> 00:35:14.109
By the way, let me just say, since I'm at
Google, we've also shown in a number of experiments

00:35:14.109 --> 00:35:20.109
that using social media, like Google Plus,
induces the release of oxytocin as well.

00:35:20.109 --> 00:35:26.540
So, connection is what we need, connection
is what we want and if you understand that

00:35:26.540 --> 00:35:30.980
that's a very deep evolutionary part of history,
a deep part of our human nature, then I think

00:35:30.980 --> 00:35:39.420
it frees you up to connect to others and to
enjoy the reduction in stress, the improvement

00:35:39.420 --> 00:35:42.859
in immune system and an increase in happiness
that you get from oxytocin release.

00:35:42.859 --> 00:35:50.820
So, I've said a lot, how about if I take some
questions and we can hang out and chat a little

00:35:50.820 --> 00:35:51.820
bit.

00:35:51.820 --> 00:35:52.820
Oh, there's no questions at all?

00:35:52.820 --> 00:35:54.660
Michael,we should let him go first cause I
picked on him.

00:35:54.660 --> 00:35:57.109
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt;Paul Zak: He's a fine person, we know that.

00:35:57.109 --> 00:36:03.519
&gt;&gt;male #1: So I have a question, um, does
the ability to perceive oxytocin change us

00:36:03.519 --> 00:36:05.839
over time in the same person?

00:36:05.839 --> 00:36:08.900
&gt;&gt;Paul Zak: That's a great question.

00:36:08.900 --> 00:36:14.349
So, there is evidence suggesting that the
more you release oxytocin, the more you lower

00:36:14.349 --> 00:36:15.369
the threshold for release.

00:36:15.369 --> 00:36:17.160
In other words it gets easier to release oxytocin.

00:36:17.160 --> 00:36:19.660
By the way, that's different than fear.

00:36:19.660 --> 00:36:24.869
So fear we acclimate to, so I can scare you
and then you get used to that stimulus and

00:36:24.869 --> 00:36:26.329
I have to keep increasing it.

00:36:26.329 --> 00:36:30.740
But with oxytocin release, it gets easier
and easier which is very interesting.

00:36:30.740 --> 00:36:35.170
Even though there's some experiments that
suggest that, my own experience is the same.

00:36:35.170 --> 00:36:39.300
Because I'm introvert, and I kind of get tired
talking to people but it turns out that the

00:36:39.300 --> 00:36:43.619
more I connect to people, the easier it gets
and, presumably, the more oxytocin I'm releasing.

00:36:43.619 --> 00:36:47.670
So, I'm subject number one in that experiment.

00:36:47.670 --> 00:36:49.569
Yeah, thanks.

00:36:49.569 --> 00:36:57.759
&gt;&gt;male #2: So, did I understand correctly
that you said you could test, establish where

00:36:57.759 --> 00:37:01.650
people were on the psychopath scale through
blood testing?

00:37:01.650 --> 00:37:05.950
&gt;&gt;Paul Zak: Yeah, we have evidence that we
can identify the psychopaths.

00:37:05.950 --> 00:37:10.730
We can't nail that exactly where they are
on a scale but if you're severe enough, this

00:37:10.730 --> 00:37:13.660
is the Hare psychopathology's checklist.

00:37:13.660 --> 00:37:17.960
If you're severe enough on a checklist, you'll
get picked up in our blood test.

00:37:17.960 --> 00:37:21.940
&gt;&gt;male #2: So are you concerned with the,
sort of, criminal justice applications of

00:37:21.940 --> 00:37:23.299
this at some point in the future?

00:37:23.299 --> 00:37:27.930
&gt;&gt;Paul Zak: Right, so I see people who I talk
to and groups I talk to who really like this

00:37:27.930 --> 00:37:31.410
work a lot are lawyers and judges because
they have these frequent fliers.

00:37:31.410 --> 00:37:38.560
So I spent a fair amount of time in courthouses
and jails interviewing these individuals to

00:37:38.560 --> 00:37:41.200
find out why they don't respond to punishments.

00:37:41.200 --> 00:37:45.750
And there's actually some very funny stories
in there and also some tragic stories.

00:37:45.750 --> 00:37:51.140
But I'm not worried about a, kind of, Brave
New World approach where, again, we're shooting

00:37:51.140 --> 00:37:52.930
this stuff into people's brains.

00:37:52.930 --> 00:37:58.020
Because, number one, the effects are fairly
subtle and, number two, these psychopaths

00:37:58.020 --> 00:38:02.130
don't seem to have the receptors for oxytocin,
so even if I replace it, having said that,

00:38:02.130 --> 00:38:05.530
there are drugs in development that can increase
the number of oxytocin receptors.

00:38:05.530 --> 00:38:11.350
And, so, those might be used to treat a variety
of disorders that associate with improper

00:38:11.350 --> 00:38:16.170
social behaviors, schizophrenia, depression,
social anxiety and maybe psychopathology.

00:38:16.170 --> 00:38:19.819
So, again, I think society needs to say where
that line lies.

00:38:19.819 --> 00:38:23.779
I need to do the basic research and show the
world what we can do with it.

00:38:23.779 --> 00:38:29.750
&gt;&gt;male #2: So, I mean, given the Hare test
is used to sort of approve or deny parole

00:38:29.750 --> 00:38:35.799
in some states, I mean, do you think that
would be a useful thing if this blood test

00:38:35.799 --> 00:38:40.410
became used eventually to, sort of, decide
people's futures?

00:38:40.410 --> 00:38:43.950
&gt;&gt;Paul Zak: Right, so I think, we're still
doing more research on this so I'd say the

00:38:43.950 --> 00:38:45.460
jury's still out.

00:38:45.460 --> 00:38:49.480
There's a funny story I tell in the book about
being pulled into a murder case.

00:38:49.480 --> 00:38:56.809
So there was an internet entrepreneur in Silicon
Valley named Hans Reiser who was getting divorced.

00:38:56.809 --> 00:39:03.670
His wife was Russian and instead of divorcing
his wife he decides, instead, to kill her.

00:39:03.670 --> 00:39:08.160
And he's on trial for this, they never find
the body, the last day of the trial he's gonna

00:39:08.160 --> 00:39:09.410
be convicted for sure.

00:39:09.410 --> 00:39:17.049
He pleads to first degree murder to avoid
the death penalty and shows the prosecutor

00:39:17.049 --> 00:39:18.900
where the body is.

00:39:18.900 --> 00:39:20.390
He goes to jail for life, he's in San Quentin.

00:39:20.390 --> 00:39:25.960
A year into San Quentin, he writes a four
page, handwritten appeal to the state of California

00:39:25.960 --> 00:39:32.859
asking for a new trial, citing my research,
claiming that his lawyer had oxytocin deficit

00:39:32.859 --> 00:39:36.410
disorder, this disorder I called, which you
don't release oxytocin.

00:39:36.410 --> 00:39:38.819
And, of course, that appeal was denied.

00:39:38.819 --> 00:39:42.589
But, I mean, the lack of insight, here's a
guy who has no empathy at all who's claiming

00:39:42.589 --> 00:39:45.339
his lawyer didn't have empathy and couldn't
represent him properly.

00:39:45.339 --> 00:39:48.220
So it's getting into the law now.

00:39:48.220 --> 00:39:56.029
So, yeah, we're, the largest group of neuroscientists
have come out the last few years saying that

00:39:56.029 --> 00:40:01.559
many of the neuroscience findings like brain
imaging, are not ready for the courtroom because

00:40:01.559 --> 00:40:08.250
they are, they can induce more bias than they
can remove uncertainty in, in people's minds.

00:40:08.250 --> 00:40:11.480
So, they're more prejudicial than they are
probative.

00:40:11.480 --> 00:40:15.539
Yeah, great question, thanks.

00:40:15.539 --> 00:40:16.559
Yeah.

00:40:16.559 --> 00:40:17.569
[Pause]

00:40:17.569 --> 00:40:28.450
&gt;&gt;male #3: Two related questions on the, assuming
that there are other factors, say besides

00:40:28.450 --> 00:40:32.450
trust, that might effect a country's prosperity
where, could you name a few countries who

00:40:32.450 --> 00:40:37.430
may have had high, um, low trust but high
prosperity?

00:40:37.430 --> 00:40:44.329
And then on the individual level is it possible,
again, similarly to, the 5 percent of people

00:40:44.329 --> 00:40:53.910
who were kind of psychopathic, is it possible
to override the oxytocin pathway process and

00:40:53.910 --> 00:40:58.920
still do some of these negative things but
have fully functioning oxytocin receptors?

00:40:58.920 --> 00:41:01.509
&gt;&gt;Paul Zak: Great question, two great questions.

00:41:01.509 --> 00:41:07.109
So, we actually ran a horse race using cross
country data which asked does this oxytocin

00:41:07.109 --> 00:41:11.530
which facilitates trust, does that come first
or do you need kind of good institutions?

00:41:11.530 --> 00:41:17.230
So, it's the institutions that actually generate
high trust and the oxytocin response to that.

00:41:17.230 --> 00:41:22.960
So those are a government that fairly enforces
contracts, independent judiciary, having a

00:41:22.960 --> 00:41:27.640
well functioning social sector so not a lot
of social strife and having a well functioning

00:41:27.640 --> 00:41:28.640
economic sector.

00:41:28.640 --> 00:41:33.530
So, for example, a very high variance in distribution
of income tends to drag down trust levels

00:41:33.530 --> 00:41:38.250
because now it's harder to understand if someone's
gonna behave nicely because they might be

00:41:38.250 --> 00:41:39.559
under survival stress.

00:41:39.559 --> 00:41:45.420
And so yeah, fixing those three sectors come
first and then the brain responds with this

00:41:45.420 --> 00:41:46.619
feeling of safety.

00:41:46.619 --> 00:41:51.890
So a great example is London or New York which,
you know, 25-30 years ago were much less safe

00:41:51.890 --> 00:41:58.660
places and have become, actually, much friendlier,
much safer and, actually, very prosperous.

00:41:58.660 --> 00:42:02.859
So, I was in New York 10 days ago, I mean,
2 in the morning you can walk around and you

00:42:02.859 --> 00:42:06.950
feel totally comfortable in Manhattan and
just about anywhere.

00:42:06.950 --> 00:42:10.519
So yeah, there are, there's this positive
feedback loop.

00:42:10.519 --> 00:42:14.099
The second question was on individuals who
don't seem to have these oxytocin receptors.

00:42:14.099 --> 00:42:21.690
So, in a short story to illustrate this point,
we ran an experiment for a TV show, which

00:42:21.690 --> 00:42:24.579
I talk about in the book, a show on the seven
deadly sins.

00:42:24.579 --> 00:42:26.700
And, so, of course I was hoping to get lust.

00:42:26.700 --> 00:42:28.130
Unfortunately, I got greed.

00:42:28.130 --> 00:42:35.730
I thought I could do lust, but anyway, the
shtick on the show was they took a woman from

00:42:35.730 --> 00:42:41.381
the Donald Trump show, The Apprentice, in
the US, and who is gorgeous, successful, but

00:42:41.381 --> 00:42:42.381
famously greedy.

00:42:42.381 --> 00:42:47.390
And we run her through a battery of trials
to understand, is she a psychopath?

00:42:47.390 --> 00:42:49.640
Is she using people?

00:42:49.640 --> 00:42:53.419
Or, so she was actually very greedy for money,
in fact, we put her on the intranasal oxytocin,

00:42:53.419 --> 00:42:56.200
it didn't affect her behavior.

00:42:56.200 --> 00:43:00.029
So, she has many of the attributes of psychopaths,
although she has a very funny developmental

00:43:00.029 --> 00:43:02.190
history which you can read up on in the book.

00:43:02.190 --> 00:43:05.359
Her father was a drug dealer, although she's
very intelligent.

00:43:05.359 --> 00:43:12.089
But, when we did other tasks with her, like
we did some cooperation tasks in which they

00:43:12.089 --> 00:43:17.119
don't involve money, she was wonderfully cooperative
and an actually very nice person but she doesn't

00:43:17.119 --> 00:43:19.109
have the underlying oxytocin release.

00:43:19.109 --> 00:43:25.310
So, she can still be a nice person when she
wants to, but when it comes to business she

00:43:25.310 --> 00:43:28.319
will take your face off if she can.

00:43:28.319 --> 00:43:31.099
So, again, we learn to modulate this.

00:43:31.099 --> 00:43:35.570
So, again, it's not just oxytocin, there's
lots of other factors that affect our social

00:43:35.570 --> 00:43:36.570
behaviors.

00:43:36.570 --> 00:43:40.499
But that was really the missing mechanism
that motivates the many positive behaviors.

00:43:40.499 --> 00:43:41.499
Yeah, thanks.

00:43:41.499 --> 00:43:46.380
&gt;&gt;male #4: So, one of the behaviors that you're
talking about, oxytocin in the brain that

00:43:46.380 --> 00:43:50.490
you're measuring it from blood before and
after samples, so I was wondering if you could

00:43:50.490 --> 00:43:54.039
talk about the difference between the oxytocin
